MOOD: When a hurricane derails your wedding plans, but you don’t GAF about what “should have been” because what matters most is the MARRIAGE & COMMITMENT. Love you, Ashley! xx

Mike & Ashley planned for an extravagant outdoor wedding weekend at the bubble gum pink Ringling Museum that sits oceanside in Saratoga, Florida. Hurricane Ian had other plans, and I am so proud of all the vendors who rallied to make this event happen, especially @jenniferbuonoevents. There were many difficult roadblocks to navigate like power outages, needing to find a new venue (and venues not responding), already purchased food going bad, out-of-state vendors flying in (airports were closed due to damage), guests’ needs and layers of logistics, reconfiguring event design to a smaller space just to name a few. It takes a village to make that kind of magic happen and although it does hurt my heart a bit to know ‘what could have been’, what resonates more is the leadership, calmness, and camaraderie between all the vendors to make it happen for this couple. In addition, @vivantrentals deserves a special shout out too - they worked their tails off to re-imagine custom furniture that took months to design/create and in a matter of days. An ugly ballroom never looked SO GOOD. 

Here’s a glimpse of the energy of that weekend, but check my stories for more playful nuances.

Inspired by Milly & David’s Mikvah & sunrise dip the morning of their wedding in Tahoe (see the last frame), Anna wanted a similar experience of her own on her wedding day. So along with her BFFs, they made their way to the shoreline, she quickly undressed except for her wedding veil and danced her way across the rocky sand. What I had envisioned in this moment was the second frame, but this first one is my most treasured memory from that morning.

I choose this career. And my why is rooted deeply in capturing what’s most meaningful. I’m an artist and the beauty I feel in the moment might look ordinary or mundane to some, but for me, it fuels my soul, it’s moments like these that feel so alive and what I crave the most. These are the kind of moments that live on, that story tell, that make you say “remember when…”. I seriously can’t love my clients and this career more. To Anna, (and all my amazing clients) thank you for trusting me! This was fun.

I studied photography in college & one thing that was drilled into me was ‘getting noticed/hired by art directors/art buyers’ is the end goal. I’m not in the commercial world, but I’ve always held onto that hierarchy, and so when other creatives seek me out to work together, I find it the highest honor & form of flattery. 

Last year, @jasmineraecakes commissioned me to take her portrait. We talked through many ideas and I kept going back to the power of dynamic illustrative portraiture.  How could we showcase her art in an understated elegant way? How can I tell a story in just a picture and no words? Photographing her creating her cakes felt expected and not the direction I wanted to go in. 

There’s this photo of Steve Martin that @samjonespictures took - it’s of him with a million bananas in the background. Just google “Steve Martin Bananas” and it will come up. Sam said “too often in photography we see images that are visually interesting, but give us no greater context about who the person in the photograph is. When you can say something visually about your subject that creates a window into their personality, career path, or philosophy, you are really harnessing the power of photography. It doesn’t happen often, but in portrait photography, that should always be the goal.” I couldn’t agree more. Nailed it. 

The collaborative process began. My attitude is very ‘go big or go home’ and our efforts were ambitious!  Like the “bananas” photo, I wanted Jasmine to be standing/sitting among her cakes and that’s when I suggested we team up with a stylist. @kaeskitsko with @otherhalfevents was the *perfect* fit to bring this idea to life. This photo was taken in Jasmine’s studio, which once had a white wall, and I strongly urged Jasmine to create a textured background of sorts. She did and it was perfect. We played around with different lighting techniques, some moody, some natural light, film and digital. Here are some of my faves + a sassy video at the end. Thank you Jasmine for having me. This was so fun!

Eleven years ago I photographed this wedding and never in my wildest dreams would I have thought it would be such a timeless staple in my portfolio. 

Holden (bride) used to model for me a lot in college. I met her through *model mayhem* and throughout many big asks in my collegiate career we became friends! When it was time for her wedding, naturally, she called me! At that time I was just starting to accept weddings as my career (if you don’t know - the original plan was to be an advertising photog, and really a groupie photog for bands) but alas weddings somehow fell into my lap and Holden & Ryan’s was one I’ll never forget. 

They trusted me to do my thing and little did I know the foundation I built for their wedding day would be what I still use today: creating a storyline that is MEANINGFUL. Holden & Ryan married at San Francisco City Hall, but had a large time gap between their wedding ceremony and reception later that evening. So we brainstormed what our time together would look like. They actually met IRL while smoking cigarettes and drinking coffee at @cafedelapressesf in Union Square. Something along the line of sitting at close-by tables and starting a convo kind of romance. At that point, it was a no-brainer to suggest going to the very place they met after they exchanged vows and made it official. 

Swipe through to see a few favorites and check my website for the rest of their story. 

Clients are hiring not only for my ability to capture candid moments, but it’s the art director / creative director in me that people gravitate towards. All I ever want is for the day to feel as authentic as any other day would feel, except maybe you’re just dressed in white and getting married. 😉

So much to unpack with this last-minute elopement in the Napa Valley. What was to be a wedding in Colorado, quickly changed to nuptials in Napa due to a flood devastating this couple’s wedding venue. 

I have a few favorite moments and stories to share from this wedding. 

Image No. 1: Besides the fact that this image feels very small-town Americana (thanks American flags) what cracks me up the most is that the groom was calling his mom to verify her maiden name for their marriage documents. 

Image No. 2: They had envisioned a beautiful outdoor ceremony in the vineyards, but that was not the case when we arrived to the Napa courthouse. Instead, we were put into a room with fluorescent lighting and enjoyed the view of a mural of vineyards framed by curtains. I remember Lora’s face when she first saw it, on the brink of a meltdown, but my attitude was very much “this is so cool” because it was beyond cheesy. We embraced the silliness and this photo reflects their laughter and relief in that moment. 

Image No. 3. There’s no real good story here except that I have been capturing my clients eating food for 10+ years. Just saying. Also, the bride is a pastry chef, so it was must - and meaningful - to stop at Bouchon for a quick bite. 

Image No. 6. We had to embrace the cheese with a classic prom pose. 

Image No. 7. Perhaps this is where my cheekiness began. Her stockings make it for me tho. 

Every last bit captured on film. More on my website!

If you ask me what pure joy looks like - I’d tell you about Romi and Bunny; their happiness was contagious. I feel emotions deeply (it’s called clairsentience if you really want to know) and the purity of their connection and love is probably the most profound that I have witnessed. 

They originally hired me for an elopement at city hall, just us. And they quickly realized that although SF City Hall is beautiful, that kind of ceremony wasn’t suited for them. Instead, they created a meaningful interfaith ceremony on the beach with their loved ones. Our short time together included a ’second line’ of sorts in the streets of San Francisco with a close friend trailing the guests with his accordion musical talent.  One of my favorite moments was the group shot taken at 46th & Noriega. What makes it meaningful is the significance of that bus stop and their daily routine of riding to work together. This is what I love about what I do: something so fleeting and spontaneous becomes one of the most influential and memorable photographs from the day. 

@vignetteflorals designed the floral crowns and bouquets the couple both carried and my favorite detail were those birch branches and ribbon. A great reminder that simple can be really beautiful.

Monday night was the intersection where big dreams, big ideas, and meaningful relationships converged. @jessetombs and I hosted a dinner party at @promontorywine ushering a rainy welcome to spring and bringing us all closer together. Every aspect of the evening was thoughtfully constructed to create a magical sensory overload from sight, to taste, to touch. It’s always the unexpected moments that I hold onto the most: the bouts of rain and the fog, the conversations and the laughter, the symphony of frogs as we said goodnight. Truly a dream come true.

It was just a coincidence that my birthday coincided with @engagesummits this year and SICILY you did not disappoint. It’s me, the wild one in the neon, having the time of her life. Thank you @allanzepedaphoto for capturing my spirit that night. 

To sum up this experience in just ten images is impossible and I am struggling to find the words to express how this experience meant to me. Let’s just say that the energy of each and every person at this event was kismet. Something so intangible you had to be there to fully grasp the feeling. It was perfect. 

I will never forget the kindness and love I experienced on this trip. I deepened old relationships and made new ones. I’m entering a new decade and it’s already full of spontaneity, curiosity, and excitement.  I am very clear on who I am and I know I’m exactly where I am supposed to be. 

This trip was also met with some of the saddest moments of my life. The very reason I am a photographer, my favorite person on the planet, my grandpa, passed away on my birthday. There were so many angels on my side, especially @venuseverest who picked me up and brought me back to life. I will never forget running hand in hand with you to the dance floor to celebrate my birthday at midnight. A few days later, with my husband on our next adventure in Sicily, there was a painted world map signed “Gary”. He meant the world to me as I know I did him. And even more so, I see this as a sign that he’s always with me no matter where I am in the world, and that the world is here for me, to travel and experience the life I always wanted. I’m so lucky to have felt his unconditional love my entire life. All now he can watch from above the foundation and legacy he instilled in me. I know he is proud.

If there’s one thing you should know about me, it’s that my biggest inspiration in photography comes from flipping through old family photos.  There’s something so raw, real, and imperfect about those kinds of photographs - life documented as it happened. Perfection is boring. I want a story, I want movement, I want to feel something when I look at photographs. 

When I look at these photos, it reminds me of just that. There’s something pure about the sweetness of young love. 

For Kelci & Blake, we created a day that felt like them. Hanging out in one of their favorite neighborhoods in the city, grabbing a meatball sandwich, finding a bottle of wine at one of their fave corner stores, and walking up to Coit Tower to take in that beautiful San Francisco city view. Cinematic, romantic, and real, just ust the way I like it. That’s all I ever want for my clients — photos that make you feel something - photos that remind you of what right now feels like. There’s nothing better. 

You have to ask yourself, how do you want RIGHT NOW to be captured? 

Can’t wait for your wedding this Summer, Kelci & Blake. xoxo @katesiegelevents.

Not to get all mushy today, but I just wrapped up a marathon of four beautiful wedding weekends in a row, and I say this a lot, but I really do love my clients. I attract some really cool cats and I find myself pinching myself in awe at who I get to meet and the stories I get to capture and share. This life I have is pretty rad and I am mushy AF right now and am inspired to share more… 

This cake-cutting photo took my breath away the first time I saw it. It’s from Sara Ruth & Lavs’s wedding last summer at the Giants Stadium in San Francisco. I love the feeling and the energy from it. ( I also love that the stadium lights allowed me to shoot 3200 black & white film at night without a video light or flash- what a treat)  But, what I can’t stop thinking about is what the groom said to me right after this happened. I’m paraphrasing, but he said: “You wanna know what’s funny Christina, I hate cake”. And we stood there and laughed. It’s such a breath of fresh air when my clients can just be so real. 

A story within a story. Every wedding I photograph has similar moments and I’m going to do my best to start sharing them more. Even as I compose this caption I have the biggest smile on my face and it reminds me of why I do what I do. The energy and buoyancy in these kinds of fleeting moments is what I live for and hold onto the most.

I’ve been doing a lot of introspective work lately. I think a lot about my foundation, my values, my goals, and most importantly what my legacy is.  What haunts me the most is working on a signature style: one that’s just mine, that looks like me and feels like me. It’s a lifetime challenge that I continue to invest in and work at and not something that happens overnight. It’s easy to get lost in the sea of the same old, same old, or jumping on trend chains, or pumping out work like a factory, but the hard work is sustaining that archetype and continuing to push boundaries. 

Moments like these frames excite me. It’s easy to brush this off as “magic” or “luck” (thank you wind) but it’s layered. I am actively seeking vulnerability in my subjects, and the secret is by being vulnerable myself. There’s art in how I am directing, the energy that I bring and the playfulness that ensues. And with certainty, my legacy is not boring or vanilla. It’s extra. It’s always extra, chocolatey, velvety, extra. 

Thank you Diana & Jos for being vulnerable with me. This day felt like scenes plucked from a movie. And I promise you, I will never forget how we all felt that day. So fun. So much magic! Shared with permission. As much as I love a nekkid photo — I respect my clients' privacy and boundaries more. I am so appreciative to my clients for allowing me to create art (and share it).

P.S. If you’re still here and reading, I’d love to know:  Can you name an artist without seeing their name? (You know a Wes Anderson film when you see one). Can you say the same for your work? This literally haunts me. Just a thought for a Friday afternoon…

Every year I do an exercise where I write down all the things I accomplished month-by-month. This list is a reminder of my growth, especially when I feel like I didn’t do a damn thing. I’m a pro at manifesting and getting what I want: I work hard, I make lists, and I tackle them. But this year was different. My word for 2023 was “surrender” & I didn’t create that list. I wanted to see how my ’type a” self would do without planning every aspect of my life. Can I survive a year where life just happens? This was the year of putting my family first. My excuse is always “I’m too busy” so instead I visited my dad in Arkansas & surprised my grandpa for his 89th bday. Two months later my grandpa died on my birthday. Life is funny sometimes. 

This year I have serendipitously made the best of friends with like-minded Great Dane mamas. My life revolves around my dogs’ happiness after all. I told my friend Sinee (@eloisethegreatdane) on one of our daily walks that my one goal for 2023 was to photograph a celeb wedding. I didn’t know how or when (hello “surrender”) but I hit that goal in May. I feel incredibly cheeseball even talking about this for several reasons, but most of all bragging about yourself isn’t really cool, and you gotta stay humble and gracious. But like, for real, when are we allowed to just say “I’m so proud of myself?!”. I don’t take these things for granted. I feel lucky that like-minded, cool, KIND, clients continually choose me. Like attracts like. 

I’m writing this as a cathartic need and reminder when I’m feeling down, or lost, or finding myself in the compare game and thinking I’m not good enough that: It's OK to surrender. It’s OK to take the road less traveled. It’s OK to be exactly who you are. It’s OK to be sensitive. It’s OK to celebrate your wins.

INTRODUCING SESH! 

I am pumped to launch my first SESH in SAN FRANCISCO. Join me for a jam-packed two-day intensive mentorship kind of experience in my home in San Francisco. It’s happening Feb 6-8, 2024. Nera & Jim’s wedding, in its entirety, was such a thoughtful example of a cohesive wedding design. It was an intimate neoclassical wedding, with a strong emphasis on Ancient Greek and Mediterranean aesthetics. 

I nearly gasped when I saw the mural, an original custom painting reproduced as a large canvas for guests to enjoy during dinner & dancing. An understated statement piece (with many meaningful easter eggs painted throughout) that helped weave the wedding design together. The original artwork was first used in the invitation suite, then seen at cocktail hour as panels on the custom bar, and then again during dinner. 

My favorite photo is the second one (scroll right). It just hits differently;  it was unexpected and I felt like I was in a museum. Truthfully, it was NEXT LEVEL. I have never seen a cake have such a moment. The cake was a simple white bas-relief work of art and together it felt like the most perfect harmonious complement. I still can’t get over it.

It’s not every day you get to ride along with your newlywed couple to their after-party in a 60’s Impala. I can be a pretty sentimental person and Kelci & Blake, old souls who value nostalgia, and tradition and who are excellent at tying meaning together made my night by making sure to play Otis Redding’s “Sittin’ On the Dock of the Bay” as headlights beamed in our eyes along Napa’s highway 37. 

It just so happened that when I photographed their engagement session in San Francisco I serendipitously started singing the same song. I’m not a singer! But it felt right, especially as they sipped wine from the bottle and took in the view of the city.  Quickly after I turned on Spotify to really capture that mood. They got me!

Moments like these are the ones I hold onto the most. I guess my bad singing, in that moment, at Coit Tower overlooking North Beach, really meant something to them too.
